---
title: Creamy Dill Salmon with Couscous & Green Beans
description: Another work day, another dinner daydream. You know what we mean. You’re sitting at your desk and 2:00 p.m. rolls around. Suddenly, all you can think is, “Dinner...what the heck am I going to eat for dinner?!” Well, we’ve got you covered, and FYI, the answer to that question is pretty darn delicious. We’re serving up succulent pork tenderloin with roasted green beans and savory couscous. To finish things off, the pork is drizzled with a life-affirming creamy dill sauce. Talk about a dream come true!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/645122811a2b8a8e3f068bda-1549d739.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/64caa9fd246382b42dacd0ee.pdf
cuisine: North America
author: HelloFresh
time required: 30 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 740 kcal
  fat: 49 g
  saturated fat: 16 g
  carbohydrates: 41 g
  sugar: 6 g
  protein: 36 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 610 mg
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/creamy-dill-salmon-64caa9fd246382b42dacd0ee
course: main course
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with foil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim @green beans{6%ounce} if necessary. Pick and roughly chop fronds from @dill{1/4%ounce}.

Pat @salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add salmon and sear, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{4-8%minutes} (it'll finish cooking in the next step).

Turn off heat; transfer salmon to one side of prepared baking sheet.

> Swap in chicken or salmon for pork. Cook chicken until cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook salmon (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, 5-7 minutes, then flip and cook until cooked through, 1-2 minutes more. Transfer to a cutting board to rest (no need to roast!).

Add green beans to empty side of baking sheet with salmon; toss with a drizzle of @olive oil{}, @salt{}, @pepper{}, and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste.

Roast on top rack until green beans are tender and salmon is cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Remove from oven; transfer salmon to a #cutting board{} to rest for ~{5%minutes}.

> Roast green beans without chicken or salmon.

Meanwhile, add @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce} and @butter{1%tablespoon} to a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Cook, stirring, until butter has melted and couscous is lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add 3/4 cup water, half the @chicken stock concentrate{2%unit} (you'll use more in the next step), and a big pinch of salt. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

> Drain excess water if necessary.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, heat pan used for salmon over medium-high heat. Add remaining stock concentrates and 1/4 cup water; bring to a simmer and cook ~{1-2%minutes}.

Reduce heat to low and whisk in @sour cream{3%tablespoon}, half the chopped dill, and @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon} to taste. Turn off heat. Stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} and any resting juices from salmon. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{} and season with salt and pepper.

Slice salmon crosswise.

> Slice chicken crosswise (skip slicing salmon!).

Divide couscous, salmon, and green beans between plates. Spoon sauce over salmon and sprinkle with remaining chopped dill and any remaining chili flakes to taste. Serve.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.